snippet.textDisplay:
Delicious, but I wish I waited for the recipe. Followed the video and I had to get creative. A double batch of that spoken recipe did not net me near enough shortbread dough to even coat the bottom of a lasagna pan. Pretty sure my pan is the same as in video, or maybe Babish and the pan are each miniature. I didn't have the butter to make double the double batch, but I had enough for a bread loaf pan. I baked and constructed in that. My caramel came out with a grainy texture, which was surely entirely my bad. I was using a cheap meat thermometer, it was acting up, and I kept forgetting to stir frequently. If I didn't get the caramel right, you betchya the chocolate didn't temper properly.


It was a fun, messy endeavor. It looks and tastes great even though things went wrong. I will use another recipe for this in the future if Babish doesn't upload his own. Tried following the video, but something didn't seem right with the volumes.

snippet.textDisplay: Mate, I think you need to heat your caramel to a higher temperature. None of your sucrose will caramelise at 113 °C (236 °F). If you take it to 150 °C (300 °F), your butter will become beurre noisette as well, giving a nice nutty note to your caramel. Also, you don't cream your butter and sugar for your shortbread. Do you not find that results in a dense and chewy shortbread?
